AUDIO_CONTENT_Title: The Weight of Silence
Chapter One: The Day the Sky Stayed Still

The sky over Kitala had always moved.

Even on the hottest days, when the sun pressed down like a heavy hand and the air refused to stir, there was always something—thin clouds dragging themselves across the blue, birds stitching invisible patterns between the hills, wind whispering through banana leaves. Motion was as constant as breath.

Until the day it stopped.

At first, no one noticed.

Miriam was at the well when it happened, lowering the bucket with the same steady rhythm she had practiced since childhood. The rope slid through her hands, rough and familiar. A bead of sweat rolled down her temple, tracing the same path it always did. Everything felt exactly as it should.

Then the bucket hit the water—but there was no sound.

She paused.

Not because silence was unusual. Kitala knew silence. It came in the early mornings before the goats stirred, in the long pauses between distant thunder. But this was different. This silence didn’t sit around sound—it replaced it.

Miriam leaned forward, peering into the well.

The water below was perfectly still.

No ripples. No echo. Not even the faint shimmer of movement.

She tugged the rope sharply.

The bucket rose, heavy with water, but the surface below remained untouched—as if nothing had disturbed it at all.

“That’s strange,” she muttered.

Behind her, a child laughed.

She turned instinctively, expecting to see little Kato chasing chickens again. His laughter always came in bursts, high and bright.

But when she looked—

His mouth was open.

His face was alive with joy.

And yet, no sound came out.

Miriam’s breath caught.

“Kato?” she called.

Her voice felt wrong. She could feel it leaving her throat, shaping itself into the familiar syllables—but it didn’t reach her ears.

The world had swallowed it.

A slow, creeping unease began to settle in her chest.

Around the village, life continued—women grinding millet, men repairing fences, children running barefoot through dust—but something had shifted. Movements were slightly off, like a dance where the music had been cut but no one had told the dancers.

Miriam dropped the rope.

The bucket plunged back into the well, but again—no splash.

Now others were starting to notice.

A woman clapped her hands sharply, frowning when nothing followed. A man shouted toward the hills, his face tightening as his own voice failed to return. Goats bleated soundlessly, their mouths opening in silent protest.

The silence was no longer empty.

It was heavy.

Oppressive.

Watching.

Miriam’s heart began to race.

She pressed her hands over her ears, then pulled them away. No difference. The silence wasn’t something she could block out—it was everywhere.

And then—

The sky stopped.

She didn’t see it happen. No one did. It was the kind of change that slipped in between moments, unnoticed unt